[30;1m10965 | [0m[35mexpression, while numerical differentiation can introduce round\sphinxhyphen{}off errors[0m
[30;1m10966 | [0m[35min the discretization process and cancellation. Both classical methods have[0m
[30;1m10967 | [0m[35mproblems with calculating higher derivatives, where the complexity and[0m

[30;1m10970 | [0m[35mfor gradient\sphinxhyphen{}based optimization algorithms. Algoritmic differentiation[0m
[30;1m10971 | [0m[35msolves all of these problems.[0m

[30;1m89 | [0m[35mdifferentiation scheme must work differently, since differentiation is a point estimate.[0m

[30;1m36 | [0m[35mexpression, while numerical differentiation can introduce round-off errors[0m
[30;1m37 | [0m[35min the discretization process and cancellation. Both classical methods have[0m
[30;1m38 | [0m[35mproblems with calculating higher derivatives, where the complexity and[0m
[30;1m39 | [0m[35merrors increase. Finally, both classical methods are slow at computing the[0m
[30;1m40 | [0m[35mpartial derivatives of a function with respect to many inputs, as is needed[0m
[30;1m41 | [0m[35mfor gradient-based optimization algorithms. Algoritmic differentiation[0m
[30;1m42 | [0m[35msolves all of these problems.[0m
